      "writtenOn": "2026-03-29T12:32:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "One thing to keep in mind is that Bazel doesn’t handle mixing test classes and helper classes (without `@Test` methods) very well. This has been a known limitation for quite some time (see [1]).\n\nUsing a separate testutils target works around that, but it also complicates the build setup a bit, since it requires pulling in plugin API and acceptance framework dependencies like:\n\n```\n\"//plugins:plugin-lib\",\n\"//java/com/google/gerrit/acceptance:lib\",\n```\n\nwhich are otherwise added automatically by the `gerrit_plugin_tests` macro.\n\nIn Gerrit core we usually handle this differently by keeping helper/base classes in the same test target and annotating them with `@Ignore` if they don’t contain tests (see `RawMailMessage`). This keeps Bazel happy without introducing additional build targets.\n\nIn this case, the split seems to have been introduced mainly for a single helper class: `DynamicItemUtil`. Since that utility is no longer needed (we can use `DynamicItem.itemOf(...)` from gerrit core instead), we could simplify things and revert back to the original structure.\n\n[1]: https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_java/issues/330",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 48,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 65,
        "endChar": 1
      },
      "revId": "5848b49249d470ed65738b857ad5bb85068f179d",
      "serverId": "173816e5-2b9a-37c3-8a2e-48639d4f1153"
    },
